com.google.api.client.googleapis.media
Class MediaHttpUploader

java.lang.Object
  com.google.api.client.googleapis.media.MediaHttpUploader

public final class MediaHttpUploader
extends java.lang.Object

Media HTTP Uploader, with support for both direct and resumable media uploads. Documentation is available here.

If the provided InputStream has InputStream.markSupported() as false then it is wrapped in an BufferedInputStream to support the InputStream.mark(int) and InputStream.reset() methods required for handling server errors.

Implementation is not thread-safe.

Since:
1.9
Author:
rmistry@google.com (Ravi Mistry)

directUploadEnabled

private boolean directUploadEnabled
Determines whether direct media upload is enabled or disabled. If value is set to true then a direct upload will be done where the whole media content is uploaded in a single request If value is set to false then the upload uses the resumable media upload protocol to upload in data chunks. upload

public HttpResponse upload(GenericUrl initiationRequestUrl)
                    throws java.io.IOException
Executes a direct media upload or resumable media upload conforming to the specifications listed here.

This method is not reentrant. A new instance of MediaHttpUploader must be instantiated before upload called be called again.

If an error is encountered during the request execution the caller is responsible for parsing the response correctly. For example for JSON errors: 

    if (!response.isSuccessStatusCode()) {
      throw GoogleJsonResponseException.from(jsonFactory, response);
    }

serverErrorCallback

public void serverErrorCallback()
                         throws java.io.IOException
The call back method that will be invoked by MediaUploadExponentialBackOffPolicy.getNextBackOffMillis() if it encounters a server error. This method should only be used as a call back method after upload(GenericUrl) is invoked.

This method will query the current status of the upload to find how many bytes were successfully uploaded before the server error occurred. It will then adjust the HTTP Request object used by the BackOffPolicy to contain the correct range header and media content chunk.

Throws:
java.io.IOException

getNextByteIndex

private long getNextByteIndex(java.lang.String rangeHeader)
Returns the next byte index identifying data that the server has not yet received, obtained from the HTTP Range header (E.g a header of "Range: 0-55" would cause 56 to be returned). null or malformed headers cause 0 to be returned.

Parameters:
rangeHeader - in the HTTP response
Returns:
the byte index beginning where the server has yet to receive data
